their car experience.

00:27:37.510 --> 00:27:39.560
GREG NEISWANDER: As
German just mentioned,

00:27:39.560 --> 00:27:41.650
we have this responsibility
to the driver.

00:27:41.650 --> 00:27:43.780
And part of that
responsibility is understanding

00:27:43.780 --> 00:27:47.260
that humans simply aren't as
capable inside the car when

00:27:47.260 --> 00:27:48.200
they're driving.

00:27:48.200 --> 00:27:51.690
We're just not as good at
interacting with technology,

00:27:51.690 --> 00:27:54.700
because we have this competing
safety critical activity

00:27:54.700 --> 00:27:56.680
that we have to
pay attention to.

00:27:56.680 --> 00:27:59.430
So we have to be very
careful and weigh things

00:27:59.430 --> 00:28:02.270
very carefully,
every design decision

00:28:02.270 --> 00:28:06.260
against the implications of
the effects and the effects

00:28:06.260 --> 00:28:08.970
that it might have
on human performance.

00:28:08.970 --> 00:28:11.660
And there's this
critical balance here.

00:28:11.660 --> 00:28:15.080
Essentially, one of the
cruxes of really developing

00:28:15.080 --> 00:28:17.570
experiences inside the
car is, how can you

00:28:17.570 --> 00:28:19.590
deliver a positive
user experience

00:28:19.590 --> 00:28:21.450
while at the same
time making sure

00:28:21.450 --> 00:28:24.930
that we're not
overtaxing the driver?

00:28:24.930 --> 00:28:28.280
And that leads us to
this very typical process

00:28:28.280 --> 00:28:29.800
of research and design.

00:28:29.800 --> 00:28:33.070
So this is a pretty
common iterative cycle

00:28:33.070 --> 00:28:34.747
that you see in most
development cycles.

00:28:34.747 --> 00:28:36.330
But I point it out
because it's really

00:28:36.330 --> 00:28:40.180
absolutely critical for our team
to have this close hand in hand

00:28:40.180 --> 00:28:41.730
process.

00:28:41.730 --> 00:28:44.540
And we really overly
invest in research,

00:28:44.540 --> 00:28:47.270
in our research
because distraction

00:28:47.270 --> 00:28:48.520
is such a critical issue.

00:28:48.520 --> 00:28:51.850
So we need this tightly coupled
process between the two,

00:28:51.850 --> 00:28:55.290
because it really helps
to facilitate rapid design

00:28:55.290 --> 00:28:58.170
and helps us to head in the
right direction early on,

00:28:58.170 --> 00:29:00.560
rather than having to
course correct later

00:29:00.560 --> 00:29:03.900
on when it's more costly.

00:29:03.900 --> 00:29:07.760
And that leads us more or less
to trying to test everything.

00:29:07.760 --> 00:29:10.490
So a lot of the principles
and the patterns

00:29:10.490 --> 00:29:14.040
that you see from
Android Auto aren't

00:29:14.040 --> 00:29:16.160
a random set of
ideas and theories

00:29:16.160 --> 00:29:17.610
that we've just arrived on.

00:29:17.610 --> 00:29:20.720
They're the result of a
highly intuitive process

00:29:20.720 --> 00:29:25.050
that's predominantly led by
vast amounts of user testing.

00:29:25.050 --> 00:29:28.960
So we rigorously test again
and again, as much as we can.

00:29:28.960 --> 00:29:30.840
And we have a lot
of tools and methods

00:29:30.840 --> 00:29:32.890
that we use, both on
the qualitative side

00:29:32.890 --> 00:29:35.470
